as compared to the other two

00:33:25.850 --> 00:33:29.700
ways of tempering the unfortunate
side effects of our current lack

00:33:29.700 --> 00:33:33.060
of formalities, is that
it in no way undermines

00:33:33.060 --> 00:33:37.062
the right of copyright owners who
want to retain all of their rights.

00:33:37.062 --> 00:33:41.940
It is this optional feature that
prompted Jack Valenti, the former head

00:33:41.940 --> 00:33:44.070
of the Motion Picture
Association of America

00:33:44.070 --> 00:33:49.094
and a staunch defender of copyright,
to endorse Creative Commons.

00:33:49.094 --> 00:33:50.010
[BEGIN VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:33:50.010 --> 00:33:52.830
I'm glad to be here via this video.

00:33:52.830 --> 00:33:55.650
I wish I could be there in person.

00:33:55.650 --> 00:34:00.010
But I wanted to say just few words
about Larry Lessig's concept of Creative

00:34:00.010 --> 00:34:02.400
Commons.

00:34:02.400 --> 00:34:05.800
I'm attracted to it for
the following reasons.

00:34:05.800 --> 00:34:10.210
First, Larry makes it clear
that he is respectful of

00:34:10.210 --> 00:34:17.429
and supports copyright-- copyrighted
material that artists create.

00:34:17.429 --> 00:34:20.130
And he believes it
ought to be protected.

00:34:20.130 --> 00:34:22.650
But he also says, and
I agree, that there

00:34:22.650 --> 00:34:25.520
are those people who have
copyrighted material who

00:34:25.520 --> 00:34:29.230
may want to give up part of
their copyright or all of it,

00:34:29.230 --> 00:34:32.790
to put on the Creative Commons and
let other people view it or hear it

00:34:32.790 --> 00:34:33.850
or whatever.

00:34:33.850 --> 00:34:35.580
And I have no problem with that.

00:34:35.580 --> 00:34:39.360
I think that's part of the free
and society in this country,

00:34:39.360 --> 00:34:42.790
that if you want other
people to have your material

00:34:42.790 --> 00:34:47.210
you have created free of charge
with your permission, wonderful.

00:34:47.210 --> 00:34:54.230
And I find that to be a
salutary kind of thing.

00:34:54.230 --> 00:34:58.180
But I think it's also important,
as Larry staunchly believes,

00:34:58.180 --> 00:35:00.680
that those people who have
copyrighted material-- whether it

00:35:00.680 --> 00:35:04.960
be in a book or a television
program or home video

00:35:04.960 --> 00:35:11.990
or music or movie or computer software--
and who want it protected, so that they

00:35:11.990 --> 00:35:16.790
can make sure that it can move
through the various venues

00:35:16.790 --> 00:35:19.690
where that material is
brought to the public

00:35:19.690 --> 00:35:23.640
and given to consumers at fair and
reasonable prices. [END PLAYBACK]

00:35:23.640 --> 00:35:28.410
The disadvantage of Creative Commons is
that the majority of copyright owners

00:35:28.410 --> 00:35:33.430
do not and will not use it, either
because they were unaware of it,

00:35:33.430 --> 00:35:38.530
don't understand it, or simply
don't want to give up any rights.

00:35:38.530 --> 00:35:42.040
Creative Commons thus
mitigates the troubling impact

00:35:42.040 --> 00:35:47.470
of our lack of formalities, but
certainly doesn't eliminate them.

00:35:47.470 --> 00:35:50.120
What else might we do
without sacrificing

00:35:50.120 --> 00:35:52.820
the clear benefits of
our current regime?

00:35:52.820 --> 00:35:56.900
I'll leave that to your
imagination and deliberation.

